 LFile Class API Reference
1. Overview & Concept
The LFile class is the core file-reading and media playback engine of the LinuxMediaLibrary framework. Derived from the LObject class, it reads local video/audio files (MP4, MKV, MOV, etc.) or image sequences, decodes them using the FFmpeg architecture, and distributes them frame-by-frame (AVFrame) synchronously to other targets (LPreview, LMixer, LOutput).
Key Capabilities:
    • Advanced Playback Control: Supports playback, pause, millisecond-precision seeking, and definition of In/Out points.
    • FFmpeg Filter Integration: Can apply real-time FFmpeg filters (avfilter) to video and audio data (e.g., color correction, deinterlacing, or audio delay).
    • Hardware Acceleration (GPU Bypass): When necessary, it can bypass CPU-based filter stages (gpu=true) to enable zero-copy rendering directly at the hardware level.
    • Synchronization: Through its internal decodeLoop and independent audio/video thread architecture, it resolves asynchronous issues such as audio_delay and video_delay by referencing hardware master clocks.
2. API Reference & Key Methods
📌 Media Playback Controls
    • void fileNameSet(const std::string& filePath)
      Sets the disk path of the media file to be played. If the engine is already running, it safely stops the previous playback and prepares the new file.
    • bool play()
      Starts media playback. It initializes FFmpeg contexts, opens codecs, and triggers decoding threads.
    • void pause(double ms = 0)
      Pauses playback. If a value greater than 0 is provided to the ms parameter (e.g., pause(5000)), the player automatically calls resume() after the specified milliseconds.
    • void resume()
      Resumes paused media from its current position.
    • void stop()
      Completely stops playback, cleans up all temporary allocations (SwsContext, SwrContext, AVFrame, etc.) in memory, and terminates decoding threads.
📌 Navigation and Playback Rate (Seeking & Rate)
These functions operate based on millisecond (ms) precision, following the Medialooks architectural standard.
    • void PosSet(double ms) / double PosGet()
      Seeks the playback position to the specified millisecond (ms) or returns the current playback position.
    • void RateSet(double rate) / double RateGet()
      Dynamically changes the playback speed (e.g., 1.0 is normal speed, 2.0 is 2x fast-forward, 0.5 is slow motion).
    • void InOutSet(double inMs, double outMs)
      Sets In (Start) and Out (End) points to play only a specific range of the file. (Setting to 0 removes the boundaries).
    • double getDurationMs()
      Returns the total duration of the loaded file in milliseconds.
📌 Format and Real-Time Filters
    • void setVideoFormat(const videoFormatProps& props)
      Determines the broadcast standard (resolution, FPS, color space) to which decoded raw pixels will be standardized before distribution (e.g., vF_HD1080_50p).
    • void addFilter(LFilter* filter)
      Attaches an LFilter object to the media file (used for tasks such as increasing video brightness or applying EQ to audio).
3. Properties and Configuration
The setProps(key, value) function is used to dynamically manage the internal behavior of the class.
Key	Value Type	Description
"loop"	"true", "false"	Automatically loops back to the start when the video ends.
"gpu"	"true", "false"	Performance mode. When "true", CPU-based avfilter stages are bypassed, and frames are sent directly to the destination.
"audio_delay"	Int (ms)	Synchronizes audio by shifting the audio track forward or backward by the specified milliseconds.
"video_delay"	Int (ms)	Delays the distribution of video frames by the specified milliseconds.
"scale_type"	String	Determines how the video fits the target format: "letter-box" (with black bars), "crop", or "stretch".
"scaling_quality"	Int	SWS Scaling quality. 0: SWS_FAST_BILINEAR, 2: SWS_BILINEAR, 3: SWS_LANCZOS.
4. Comprehensive Usage Example
The following example, prepared based on the mainwindow.cpp architecture, demonstrates how the LFile class opens a file from a playlist, attaches real-time filters, and routes the output to a preview widget.
C++
#include "LFile.h"
#include "LPreview.h"
#include "LFilter.h"
#include "LFormat.h"

// 1. Initialize Objects
LFile* myPlayer = new LFile();
LPreview* playerPreview = new LPreview();

// 2. Set Video Format (e.g., 1080p 50fps)
videoFormatProps vProps;
vProps.setVideoFormat = vF::HD1080_50p;
myPlayer->setVideoFormat(vProps);

// 3. Define Properties
myPlayer->setProps("loop", "true");           // Play in an infinite loop
myPlayer->setProps("gpu", "false");           // Set to false to enable CPU/Filter mode
myPlayer->setProps("scale_type", "letter-box"); // Preserve aspect ratio
myPlayer->setProps("scaling_quality", "2");   // Use Bilinear scaling

// 4. Add Real-Time Filters (using LFilter class)
LFilter* colorFilter = new LFilter(LFilter::Video);
colorFilter->setProps("eq", "brightness=0.1:contrast=1.2:saturation=1.5");
myPlayer->addFilter(colorFilter);

LFilter* audioDelayFilter = new LFilter(LFilter::Audio);
audioDelayFilter->setProps("adelay", "500|500"); // 500ms delay on left and right channels
myPlayer->addFilter(audioDelayFilter);

// 5. Route Output to Target (Preview)
// (myQtWidgetHandle is your UI's QOpenGLWidget reference)
playerPreview->previewEnable(myQtWidgetHandle, true, true);
playerPreview->previewObject(myPlayer);

// 6. Load File and Start Playback
myPlayer->fileNameSet("/media/videos/commercial_break.mp4");
myPlayer->play();

// To seek to 10 seconds (10000 ms) during playback:
// myPlayer->PosSet(10000.0);
